\begin_layout Standard
To show how income and substitution effects can lead to our results, we
 write down a simple model of fertility choices.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is an individual's wage, which (for now) we identify with his or her level
 of human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Raising a child takes time 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 People maximize utility composed of two subcomponents, income and the number
 of children 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 An individual's payoff is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(N)=u(Y)+aN
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\equiv(1-bN)W$
\end_inset

 is income from time not allocated to childcare, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 captures the strength of preference for children.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The basic relationship is robust to arbitrary functional forms for preference
 for children.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(N)=\frac{(W(1-bN))^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}+af(N)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is concave and guarantees an interior equilibrium; then you will again
 get that 
\begin_inset Formula $dN^{*}/dW$
\end_inset

 is signed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-1$
\end_inset

; and that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

 the relationship will be concave.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is concave and increasing.
 We treat 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as continuous, in line with the literature: this can be thought of as the
 expected number of children among people who share the same characteristics.
 The marginal benefit of an extra child is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dU}{dN}=-bWu'(Y)+a
\]

\end_inset

and the effect of an increase in wages on this marginal benefit is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}U}{dNdW}=\underbrace{-bu'(Y)}_{\textrm{Substitution effect}}\underbrace{-bYu''(Y)}_{\textrm{Income effect}}.
\]

\end_inset

The first term is negative and reflects that when 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 increases, time devoted to childcare costs more in foregone income.
 The second term is positive, since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave, and reflects that when 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is higher, the marginal loss of wages from childcare has less effect on
 overall utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the model explicitly, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be the 
\emph on
constant relative risk aversion
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y)=\frac{y^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0$
\end_inset

 parametrizes risk aversion in income.
 We then solve for the optimal fertility 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{*}$
\end_inset

 and examine the effect of wages on fertility, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dN^{*}}{dW}$
\end_inset

.
 We also refer to this as the 
\emph on
fertility-human capital relationship
\emph default
, since human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $h=W$
\end_inset

.
 We show the following facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If risk aversion is not too high (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

), the fertility-human capital relationship is negative: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dN^{*}}{dW}<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5<\sigma<1$
\end_inset

, the fertility-human capital relationship is weaker (i.e.
 closer to zero) at higher wages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The fertility-human capital relationship is more negative when the time
 burden of children, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, is larger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implication of the last point is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is higher for single parents than for couples, then the fertility-human
 capital relationship will be more negative for single parents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under these assumptions, polygenic scores which cause, or even correlate
 with, variation in human capital would show the pattern we observe in our
 data.
 They would have a negative correlation with fertility at low income levels,
 and a smaller or zero correlation at high income levels.
 The correlation would be more negative when the time burden of children
 is high, e.g.
 for single parents.
 These predictions fit the patterns in our data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To examine education and age at first birth, we extend this model to two
 periods.
 For convenience we ignore time discounting and assume the interest rate
 is 0; we also assume that credit markets are imperfect so that agents cannot
 save or borrow.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(N_{1},N_{2})=u(Y_{1})+u(Y_{2})+a(N_{1}+N_{2})\label{eq:U}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We continue to assume CRRA utility.
 We now drop the identification of human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with wages.
 Instead, we allow individuals to choose a level of education 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, which has a cost in time in period 1.
 Education increases period 2 wages, and is complementary to human capital
 
\begin_inset Formula $h>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we write the period 2 wage as 
\begin_inset Formula $w(s,h)$
\end_inset

.
 We assume the simple functional form 
\begin_inset Formula $w(s,h)=sh$
\end_inset

, and normalize period 1 wages to 1.
 Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Y_{1} & =1-s-bN_{1}\label{eq:Y1}\\
Y_{2} & =w(s,h)(1-bN_{2})\label{eq:Y2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can then derive conclusions about the relationship of human capital to
